    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Recent empirical studies have indeed shown mounting evidence that supply-side tax cuts disproportionately favor the wealthiest segments of society, making the \"trickle-down\" narrative increasingly tenuous. Many modern econometric analyses demonstrate that the primary beneficiaries of capital gains reductions are those who already hold significant assets, rather than broad-based wage earners. These studies often point to stagnant real wage growth alongside rising top-end incomes as the clearest indicator of increasing inequality following such reforms. This suggests that the intended broad economic benefits often fail to materialize for the lower and middle classes.",
      "source": "target",
